   1  # Agent
   2  
   3  A local, tool-driven coding assistant that talks to an OpenAI-compatible LLM endpoint (e.g. `llama-server` from `llama.cpp`) and runs an autonomous file/shell tool loop. It is built to survive long sessions: it checkpoints every turn, summarizes older history in the background, recovers from malformed tool calls, and catches common hallucinations before they poison context.
   4  
   5  ## Quick start
   6  
   7  1. Start an OpenAI-compatible LLM server locally. The default endpoint is `http://127.0.0.1:8080`:
   8  
   9     ```bash
  10     llama-server -m your-model.gguf --port 8080
  11     ```
  12  
  13  2. (Optional) create a `config.json` in your working directory to override defaults — see [Configuration](#configuration).
  14  
  15  3. Run the agent:
  16  
  17     ```bash
  18     python agent.py "fix the failing test in tests/test_parser.py"
  19     ```
  20  
  21  ## CLI
  22  
  23  ```
  24  python agent.py [OPTIONS] [PROMPT...]
  25  ```
  26  
  27  | Flag | Description |
  28  | --- | --- |
  29  | `-a`, `--auto` | Automation mode — run the prompt and exit; no interactive loop. |
  30  | `-c`, `--continue` | Resume from the last checkpoint (picks up a crashed or interrupted cycle). |
  31  | `-r N`, `--repeat N` | Run the prompt `N` times with fresh state each run. `0` or omitted means run indefinitely. Implies `-a`. |
  32  | `--nudge` | When the model returns a text-only response (no tool calls), auto-nudge it to keep going instead of stopping. Off by default. |
  33  | `PROMPT...` | Initial prompt. Optional; in interactive mode you'll be prompted if omitted. |
  34  
  35  Press **Escape twice** within 400ms to cancel a streaming response.
  36  
  37  ## How it works
  38  
  39  Each cycle is a turn loop:
  40  
  41  1. Build a context window from recent history plus an async summary of older history.
  42  2. Stream a response from the LLM.
  43  3. Execute any tool calls.
  44  4. Feed results back in and repeat until the model stops calling tools, a cycle limit is hit, or the user cancels.
  45  
  46  The loop has a few guardrails worth knowing about:
  47  
  48  - **Checkpointing.** Conversation history and summary state are written to `state/conversation_checkpoint.json` every turn. `--continue` resumes from there.
  49  - **Async summarization.** If a summary endpoint is configured, a background thread condenses older messages while the main model keeps working. The summary is swapped in when ready.
  50  - **Cycle limits & wind-down.** After `cycle.max_turns` turns (default 100), the agent is asked to wrap up; after `cycle.wind_down_turns` more turns it is forced to stop.
  51  - **Text-loop detection.** If the model emits the same text three times in a row, the cycle ends instead of looping forever.
  52  - **Hallucination guards.** When the model claims to have read a file it never actually read, the fabricated message is stripped and a correction injected. Malformed tool-call JSON is also salvaged heuristically.
  53  - **Tool recovery.** When a tool fails with a recognizable error (e.g. bad line numbers), `tool_recovery.py` tries to re-run it with corrected parameters via a lightweight LLM call.
  54  - **Context overflow handling.** Three consecutive HTTP 500s from the LLM endpoint are treated as context overflow — the agent trims history and retries.
  55  
  56  ## Project layout
  57  
  58  ```
  59  agent.py            # Main loop, streaming, context management, checkpointing
  60  cancel.py           # Double-escape cancel handler
  61  spinner.py          # Waiting/streaming/done visual feedback
  62  token_utils.py      # Tokenizer (Gemma) with char-based fallback
  63  tool_recovery.py    # Auto-recovery from recoverable tool errors
  64  tools/              # Built-in tools (see below)
  65    file.py           # read / write / insert / append / delete / list
  66    exec_command.py   # Shell execution with background-session support
  67    search_files.py   # Grep-like search with glob and case controls
  68    read_pdf.py       # PDF text extraction (PyMuPDF)
  69    web_fetch.py      # URL → markdown, saved to disk with inline preview
  70    think.py          # Deep-reasoning tool via a separate thinking call
  71    task_tracker.py   # Persistent task list in state/tasks.json
  72    sleep.py          # Pause execution
  73  state/              # Runtime artifacts (created on first run)
  74    conversation_checkpoint.json
  75    agent.log
  76    tasks.json
  77    cycle.txt
  78  ```
  79  
  80  Agent-specific tools can also live in `./tools/` alongside your working directory — they are auto-discovered and registered on startup.
  81  
  82  ## Configuration
  83  
  84  Drop a `config.json` in the working directory to override any of the built-in defaults. The top-level sections are:
  85  
  86  - **`llm`** — `base_url`, `model`. The OpenAI-compatible endpoint and model name.
  87  - **`generation`** — `temperature`, `top_p`, `top_k`, `presence_penalty`.
  88  - **`context`** — `ctx_size`, `max_tokens`, `max_full_lines`, `preview_lines`, `summary_threshold`, `summary_max_chars`, `max_context_messages`. Controls how history is sized and when it gets summarized.
  89  - **`cycle`** — `max_turns`, `wind_down_turns`, `max_text_only`. Per-cycle turn budget and text-only nudge cap.
  90  - **`retry`** — `max_retries`, `base_delay_seconds`, `max_delay_seconds`, `backoff_multiplier`, `jitter_factor`. Exponential backoff for transient LLM errors.
  91  - **`summary`** — `enabled`, `base_url`, `model`, `max_wait_on_save`. Optional separate summarization endpoint (default port 8082).
  92  
  93  Example minimal override:
  94  
  95  ```json
  96  {
  97    "llm": { "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8080", "model": "gemma-4-31B" },
  98    "context": { "ctx_size": 32768 },
  99    "cycle": { "max_turns": 50 }
 100  }
 101  ```
 102  
 103  ## Dependencies
 104  
 105  - Python 3.7+
 106  - `requests` — HTTP to the LLM endpoint
 107  - `transformers` + `torch` — Gemma tokenizer (optional; falls back to a character-based estimate if missing)
 108  - `PyMuPDF` (`fitz`) — PDF extraction, used by `tools/read_pdf.py`
 109  - `markdownify` — HTML → Markdown conversion, used by `tools/web_fetch.py`
 110  - A running OpenAI-compatible LLM server (e.g. `llama-server`)
 111  - Bash, and a TTY for the cancel handler
 112  
 113  ## State and logs
 114  
 115  Everything runtime lives under `state/`:
 116  
 117  - `conversation_checkpoint.json` — last checkpoint for `--continue`
 118  - `agent.log` — detailed per-turn log
 119  - `tasks.json` — persistent task list used by the `task_tracker` tool
 120  - `cycle.txt` — monotonic cycle counter
 121  
 122  Delete the `state/` directory to start completely fresh.

